      "map_id": 33019,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C) Hydroxyurea is contraindicated in the management of the disease</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Hydroxyurea </strong>is actually recommended for the <strong>management of sickle cell anemia in children </strong>as it <strong>reduces the frequency of painful crises </strong>and <strong>acute chest syndrome</strong>. <strong>Sickle cell anemia </strong>is a <strong>hemoglobinopathy </strong>characterized by <strong>sickle-shaped RBCs</strong>, and patients are at risk for a variety of complications, including <strong>acute chest syndrome and stroke</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A.</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<strong>These are the clinical features of sickle cell anemia</strong>: <strong>True</strong>, the presentation of severe bone pain, fever, jaundice, and the peripheral smear findings are indicative of sickle cell anemia.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B.</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<strong>The child is at risk for developing acute chest syndrome</strong>: <strong>True</strong>, patients with sickle cell anemia are at increased risk for acute chest syndrome, a severe and life-threatening complication.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D.</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<strong>The child is at risk for developing stroke</strong>: <strong>True</strong>, children with sickle cell anemia have a higher risk of stroke due to the occlusion of blood vessels in the brain by sickled cells.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Patients with <strong>sickle cell disease </strong>commonly present with <strong>bone pain</strong>, <strong>fever</strong>, and <strong>jaundice </strong>due to <strong>hemolyticanemia </strong>and <strong>vaso-occlusive crises</strong>. <strong>Hydroxyurea </strong>is an important drug in the <strong>management of sickle cell anemia</strong>, as it <strong>reduces the frequency of pain episodes </strong>and the <strong>risk of acute complications</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref;</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> OP Ghai 9<sup>th</sup> Edition Page No- 339-343</span></strong></span></span></p>",
